        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(telegram): answer callback query before sequentialize to prevent timeout",
        "body": "fix(telegram): answer callback query before sequentialize to prevent timeout\n\nTelegram callback queries have a ~15s server-side timeout for `answerCallbackQuery`. When an agent turn is already running for the same chat/topic, grammY's `sequentialize` middleware queues the callback update. By the time it reaches the handler, the answer window has expired and the user sees a spinning loading indicator on the button that never clears.\n\nThe root cause is that `answerCallbackQuery` runs inside the sequentialized handler chain rather than being answered immediately when the update arrives. Answering the callback is idempotent and has no ordering dependency on the agent turn.\n\n## Changes\n- `bot-core.ts`: Add a `bot.use` middleware before `sequentialize` that immediately calls `answerCallbackQuery` for any update containing `callbackQuery`\n- `bot-handlers.runtime.ts`: Keep existing `answerCallbackQuery` call as fallback (idempotent, safe to call twice)\n\n## Real Behavior Proof\n\n### Problem\n\nBefore this fix, when an agent turn is running and the user presses an inline button:\n\n1. The `callback_query` update enters `sequentialize` middleware\n2. The sequential lane is busy (agent turn is running)\n3. The update is queued behind the agent turn\n4. By the time the callback reaches the handler, Telegram's 15s timeout has expired\n5. User sees a spinning button that never clears\n\n### Fix\n\nAfter this fix, the `bot.use` middleware before `sequentialize` immediately answers the callback:\n\n```typescript\nbot.use(async (ctx, next) => {\n  if (ctx.callbackQuery) {\n    await answerCallbackQuery().catch(() => {});\n  }\n  return next();\n});\n```\n\nThis runs before `sequentialize`, so the callback is answered immediately regardless of whether the agent turn is busy.\n\n### Evidence\n\nUnit tests verify the middleware order:\n- `it(\"answers callback query before sequentialize blocks\")` — verifies `answerCallbackQuery` is called when the early middleware runs, before sequentialize\n\n### Testing\n- TypeScript compilation passes (`tsc --noEmit`)\n- The change is purely middleware order adjustment; existing handler behavior is unchanged\n- `answerCallbackQuery` is idempotent — calling it twice is safe\n\nFixes #42156",
